          "text": "<teammate-message teammate_id=\"team-lead\">\nYou are implementing Unit 8: Discovery Controller for the reme encrypted messenger.\n\n## Task\n\nCreate `apps/client/src/discovery/` module with a controller that:\n1. Subscribes to `broadcast::Receiver<DiscoveryEvent>` from a discovery backend\n2. For each `PeerDiscovered` event, decodes TXT records to extract routing key\n3. Matches routing key against known contacts (from storage)\n4. For matched contacts, verifies identity via HTTP challenge-response\n5. On successful verification, registers the peer as an ephemeral HTTP target via the coordinator\n6. On `PeerLost`, removes the corresponding target\n7. Handles repeated `PeerDiscovered` for the same `instance_name` as updates (address change)\n8. Caps tracked peers at 256\n\n## Architecture\n\n```\napps/client/src/discovery/\n├── mod.rs          — pub mod controller; re-exports\n└── controller.rs   — DiscoveryController struct and spawn logic\n```\n\n### DiscoveryController\n\n```rust\npub struct DiscoveryController {\n    /// Maps instance_name → (TargetId, Option<PublicID>)\n    /// Tracks which discovered peers have been registered as targets\n    peer_index: HashMap<String, PeerEntry>,\n    /// Maps routing_key → Vec<PublicID> for quick contact lookup\n    contact_index: HashMap<[u8; 16], Vec<PublicID>>,\n    /// Max tracked peers\n    max_peers: usize,\n}\n\nstruct PeerEntry {\n    target_id: TargetId,\n    verified_identity: Option<PublicID>,\n    addresses: Vec<IpAddr>,\n    port: u16,\n}\n```\n\n### spawn function\n\n```rust\npub fn spawn(\n    mut events: broadcast::Receiver<DiscoveryEvent>,\n    coordinator: Arc<TransportCoordinator>,\n    contacts: Vec<(PublicID, [u8; 16])>,  // (pubkey, routing_key) pairs\n    cancel: CancellationToken,\n) -> JoinHandle<()>\n```\n\nThe spawn function creates the controller, builds the contact_index, and runs an event loop:\n\n```rust\nloop {\n    tokio::select! {\n        () = cancel.cancelled() => break,\n        event = events.recv() => {\n            match event {\n                Ok(DiscoveryEvent::PeerDiscovered(peer)) | Ok(DiscoveryEvent::PeerUpdated(peer)) => {\n                    controller.handle_discovered(peer, &coordinator).await;\n                }\n                Ok(DiscoveryEvent::PeerLost(name)) => {\n                    controller.handle_lost(&name, &coordinator);\n                }\n                Err(broadcast::error::RecvError::Lagged(n)) => {\n                    warn!(\"Discovery controller lagged by {n} events\");\n                }\n                Err(broadcast::error::RecvError::Closed) => break,\n            }\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### handle_discovered logic\n\n1. Decode TXT records via `decode_txt(&peer.txt_records)` — skip on error (warn)\n2. Check if `routing_key` matches any contact in `contact_index` — skip if no match (stranger)\n3. If `peer_index.len() >= max_peers` and this is a new peer, skip (warn)\n4. Build HTTP URL from first address + port: `http://{addr}:{port}`\n5. **Identity verification**: Use `HttpTransport::verify_identity(&url, &candidates)` to challenge the peer\n   - If verification succeeds with a `Some(pubkey)`, register as ephemeral target with `node_pubkey` set\n   - If verification fails or returns `None`, skip (debug log)\n6. Create `HttpTarget` with `HttpTargetConfig::ephemeral(url)` and add via `coordinator.add_http_target()`\n7. Store in `peer_index`\n8. If this is a repeated discovery (same `instance_name`), check if address changed — if so, use `coordinator.replace_http_target()`\n\n### handle_lost logic\n\n1. Look up `instance_name` in `peer_index`\n2. If found, call `coordinator.remove_http_target(&target_id)`\n3. Remove from `peer_index`\n\n## Key APIs Available\n\n```rust\n// Discovery types (reme-discovery crate)\nDiscoveryEvent::PeerDiscovered(RawDiscoveredPeer { instance_name, addresses: Vec<IpAddr>, port, txt_records, discovered_at })\nDiscoveryEvent::PeerLost(String)  // instance_name\ndecode_txt(&HashMap<String, String>) -> Result<(RoutingKey, u16, u8), TxtError>  // returns ([u8;16], port, version)\n\n// Coordinator API (reme-transport)\ncoordinator.add_http_target(HttpTarget)\ncoordinator.remove_http_target(&TargetId) -> bool\ncoordinator.replace_http_target(&TargetId, HttpTarget) -> bool\n\n// HTTP target construction\nHttpTargetConfig::ephemeral(url: impl Into<String>) -> HttpTargetConfig\nHttpTarget::new(config: HttpTargetConfig) -> Result<HttpTarget, TransportError>\n\n// Identity verification\nHttpTransport::verify_identity(&self, base_url: &str, candidates: &[PublicID]) -> Result<Option<PublicID>, TransportError>\n// NOTE: This is on HttpTransport, not on individual targets. You'll need to construct a temporary HttpTransport or use reqwest directly.\n// Actually, simpler approach: just make an HTTP request to {url}/api/v1/identity?challenge={b64} directly with reqwest.\n\n// TargetId construction\nTargetId::http(url: &str) -> TargetId\n```\n\n## Dependencies to add\n\nIn `apps/client/Cargo.toml`:\n- `reme-discovery = { workspace = true }` (if not already there)\n\n## Branch Setup\n\n```bash\ngit switch feat/lan-discovery\ngit switch -c feat/discovery-controller\n```\n\n## Important Design Decisions\n\n- Controller handles new-vs-updated distinction internally (repeated PeerDiscovered for same instance_name = update)\n- Identity verification uses existing `/api/v1/identity?challenge=` endpoint\n- Strangers (peers whose routing key doesn't match any contact) are ignored for now — policy hooks come in Unit 11\n- Max 256 tracked peers to prevent resource exhaustion\n- Use `TargetCapabilities::ephemeral_defaults()` for discovered targets (send only, no fetch, no quorum credit)\n\n## After Implementation\n\n1. Run `cargo test --workspace` and `cargo clippy --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings` and `cargo fmt --all -- --check`\n2. Invoke the `simplify` skill to review and clean up your changes\n3. Commit with a clear message\n4. Push and create a PR with `gh pr create --base feat/lan-discovery`\n5. Wait for CI: run `gh pr checks <PR_NUMBER>` every 30s, max 10 attempts\n6. If CI fails, fix and push again\n7. When CI passes, send a message to `reviewer` asking for code review\n8. Wait for reviewer feedback. Fix if needed, re-check CI, re-request review\n9. When approved, report completion to team lead with PR URL\n</teammate-message>",
